# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nltk
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] The **bag-of-words** (**BoW**) **model** is a model of text which uses an unordered collection (a "bag") of words.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] It is used in natural language processing and information retrieval (IR).
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] It disregards word order (and thus most of syntax or grammar) but captures multiplicity.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] The bag-of-words model is commonly used in methods of document classification where, for example, the (frequency of) occurrence of each word is used as a feature for training a classifier.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] It has also been used for computer vision.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] An early reference to "bag of words" in a linguistic context can be found in Zellig Harris's 1954 article on *Distributional Structure*.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] The following models a text document using bag-of-words.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] Each key is the word, and each value is the number of occurrences of that word in the given text document.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] It is also what we expect from a strict *JSON object* representation.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] So, as we see in the bag algebra, the "union" of two documents in the bags-of-words representation is, formally, the disjoint union, summing the multiplicities of each element.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] The BoW representation of a text removes all word ordering.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] For example, the BoW representation of "man bites dog" and "dog bites man" are the same, so any algorithm that operates with a BoW representation of text must treat them in the same way.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] Despite this lack of syntax or grammar, BoW representation is fast and may be sufficient for simple tasks that do not require word order.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] and so the BoW representation would be insufficient to determine the detailed meaning of the document.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] Implementations of the bag-of-words model might involve using frequencies of words in a document to represent its contents.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] The frequencies can be "normalized" by the inverse of document frequency, or tf–idf.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] Additionally, for the specific purpose of classification, supervised alternatives have been developed to account for the class label of a document.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] Lastly, binary (presence/absence or 1/0) weighting is used in place of frequencies for some problems (e.g., this option is implemented in the WEKA machine learning software system).
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] A common alternative to using dictionaries is the hashing trick, where words are mapped directly to indices with a hash function.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] When using a hash function, no memory is required to store a dictionary.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] In practice, hashing simplifies the implementation of bag-of-words models and improves scalability.
[src:nltk/bag-of-words-model] Collisions can occur when two words are hashed to the same index, but this happens infrequently and may function as a form of regularization.
[src:nltk/n-gram] An ***n*-gram** is a sequence of *n* adjacent symbols in a particular order.
[src:nltk/n-gram] The symbols may be *n* adjacent letters (including punctuation marks and blanks), syllables, or rarely whole words found in a language dataset; or adjacent phonemes extracted from a speech-recording dataset, or adjacent base pairs extracted from a genome.
[src:nltk/n-gram] They are collected from a text corpus or speech corpus.
[src:nltk/n-gram] If Latin numerical prefixes are used, then *n*-gram of size 1 is called a "unigram", size 2 a "bigram" (or, less commonly, a "digram") etc.
[src:nltk/n-gram] If, instead of the Latin ones, the English cardinal numbers are furtherly used, then they are called "four-gram", "five-gram", etc.
[src:nltk/n-gram] Similarly, Greek numerical prefixes such as "monomer", "dimer", "trimer", "tetramer", "pentamer", etc., or English cardinal numbers, "one-mer", "two-mer", "three-mer", etc. are used in computational biology for polymers or oligomers of a known size, called *k*-mers.
[src:nltk/n-gram] When the items are words, n-grams may also be called *shingles*.
[src:nltk/n-gram] In the context of natural language processing (NLP), the use of *n*-grams allows bag-of-words models to capture information such as word order, which would not be possible in the traditional bag of words setting.
[src:nltk/n-gram] In 1951, Shannon discussed *n*-gram models of English.
[src:nltk/n-gram] Figure 1 shows several example sequences and the corresponding 1-gram, 2-gram and 3-gram sequences.
[src:nltk/n-gram] Here are further examples; these are word-level 3-grams and 4-grams (and counts of the number of times they appeared) from the Google *n*-gram corpus.
[src:nltk/natural-language-toolkit] The **Natural Language Toolkit**, or more commonly **NLTK**, is a suite of libraries and programs for symbolic and statistical natural language processing (NLP) for English written in the Python programming language.
[src:nltk/natural-language-toolkit] It supports classification, tokenization, stemming, tagging, parsing, and semantic reasoning functionalities.
[src:nltk/natural-language-toolkit] It was developed by Steven Bird and Edward Loper in the Department of Computer and Information Science at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:nltk/natural-language-toolkit] NLTK includes graphical demonstrations and sample data.
[src:nltk/natural-language-toolkit] It is accompanied by a book that explains the underlying concepts behind the language processing tasks supported by the toolkit, plus a cookbook.
[src:nltk/natural-language-toolkit] NLTK is intended to support research and teaching in NLP or closely related areas, including empirical linguistics, cognitive science, artificial intelligence, information retrieval, and machine learning.
[src:nltk/natural-language-toolkit] NLTK has been used successfully as a teaching tool, as an individual study tool, and as a platform for prototyping and building research systems.
[src:nltk/stemming] In linguistic morphology and information retrieval, **stemming** is the process of reducing inflected (or sometimes derived) words to their word stem, base or root form—generally a written word form.
[src:nltk/stemming] The stem need not be identical to the morphological root of the word; it is usually sufficient that related words map to the same stem, even if this stem is not in itself a valid root.
[src:nltk/stemming] Algorithms for stemming have been studied in computer science since the 1960s.
[src:nltk/stemming] Many search engines treat words with the same stem as synonyms as a kind of query expansion, a process called conflation.
[src:nltk/stemming] A computer program or subroutine that stems word may be called a *stemming program*, *stemming algorithm*, or *stemmer*.
[src:nltk/stemming] A stemmer for English operating on the stem *cat* should identify such strings as *cats*, *catlike*, and *catty*.
[src:nltk/stemming] A stemming algorithm might also reduce the words *fishing*, *fished*, and *fisher* to the stem *fish*.
[src:nltk/stemming] The stem need not be a word, for example the Porter algorithm reduces *argue*, *argued*, *argues*, *arguing*, and *argus* to the stem *argu*.
[src:nltk/stemming] The first published stemmer was written by Julie Beth Lovins in 1968.
[src:nltk/stemming] This paper was remarkable for its early date and had great influence on later work in this area.
[src:nltk/stemming] Her paper refers to three earlier major attempts at stemming algorithms, by Professor John W.
[src:nltk/stemming] Tukey of Princeton University, the algorithm developed at Harvard University by Michael Lesk, under the direction of Professor Gerard Salton, and a third algorithm developed by James L.
[src:nltk/stemming] Dolby of R and D Consultants, Los Altos, California.
[src:nltk/stemming] A later stemmer was written by Martin Porter and was published in the July 1980 issue of the journal *Program*.
[src:nltk/stemming] This stemmer was very widely used and became the de facto standard algorithm used for English stemming.
[src:nltk/stemming] Porter received the Tony Kent Strix award in 2000 for his work on stemming and information retrieval.
[src:nltk/stemming] Many implementations of the Porter stemming algorithm were written and freely distributed; however, many of these implementations contained subtle flaws.
[src:nltk/stemming] As a result, these stemmers did not match their potential.
[src:nltk/stemming] To eliminate this source of error, Martin Porter released an official free software (mostly BSD-licensed) implementation of the algorithm around the year 2000.
[src:nltk/stemming] He extended this work over the next few years by building Snowball, a framework for writing stemming algorithms, and implemented an improved English stemmer together with stemmers for several other languages.
[src:nltk/stemming] The Paice-Husk Stemmer was developed by Chris D Paice at Lancaster University in the late 1980s, it is an iterative stemmer and features an externally stored set of stemming rules.
[src:nltk/stemming] The standard set of rules provides a 'strong' stemmer and may specify the removal or replacement of an ending.
[src:nltk/stemming] The replacement technique avoids the need for a separate stage in the process to recode or provide partial matching.
[src:nltk/stemming] Paice also developed a direct measurement for comparing stemmers based on counting the over-stemming and under-stemming errors.
[src:nltk/stemming] Is there any perfect stemming algorithm in English language?
[src:nltk/stemming] There are several types of stemming algorithms which differ in respect to performance and accuracy and how certain stemming obstacles are overcome.
[src:nltk/stemming] A simple stemmer looks up the inflected form in a lookup table.
[src:nltk/stemming] The advantages of this approach are that it is simple, fast, and easily handles exceptions.
[src:nltk/stemming] The disadvantages are that all inflected forms must be explicitly listed in the table: new or unfamiliar words are not handled, even if they are perfectly regular (e.g. cats ~ cat), and the table may be large.
[src:nltk/stemming] For languages with simple morphology, like English, table sizes are modest, but highly inflected languages like Turkish may have hundreds of potential inflected forms for each root.
[src:nltk/stemming] A lookup approach may use preliminary part-of-speech tagging to avoid overstemming.
[src:nltk/stemming] The lookup table used by a stemmer is generally produced semi-automatically.
[src:nltk/stemming] For example, if the word is "run", then the inverted algorithm might automatically generate the forms "running", "runs", "runned", and "runly".
[src:nltk/stemming] The last two forms are valid constructions, but they are unlikely..
[src:nltk/stemming] Suffix stripping algorithms do not rely on a lookup table that consists of inflected forms and root form relations.
[src:nltk/stemming] Instead, a typically smaller list of "rules" is stored which provides a path for the algorithm, given an input word form, to find its root form.
[src:nltk/stemming] Suffix stripping approaches enjoy the benefit of being much simpler to maintain than brute force algorithms, assuming the maintainer is sufficiently knowledgeable in the challenges of linguistics and morphology and encoding suffix stripping rules.
[src:nltk/stemming] Suffix stripping algorithms are sometimes regarded as crude given the poor performance when dealing with exceptional relations (like 'ran' and 'run').
[src:nltk/stemming] The solutions produced by suffix stripping algorithms are limited to those lexical categories which have well known suffixes with few exceptions.
[src:nltk/stemming] This, however, is a problem, as not all parts of speech have such a well formulated set of rules.
[src:nltk/stemming] Lemmatisation attempts to improve upon this challenge.
[src:nltk/stemming] Prefix stripping may also be implemented.
[src:nltk/stemming] Of course, not all languages use prefixing or suffixing.
[src:nltk/stemming] Suffix stripping algorithms may differ in results for a variety of reasons.
[src:nltk/stemming] One such reason is whether the algorithm constrains whether the output word must be a real word in the given language.
[src:nltk/stemming] Some approaches do not require the word to actually exist in the language lexicon (the set of all words in the language).
[src:nltk/stemming] Alternatively, some suffix stripping approaches maintain a database (a large list) of all known morphological word roots that exist as real words.
[src:nltk/stemming] These approaches check the list for the existence of the term prior to making a decision.
[src:nltk/stemming] Typically, if the term does not exist, alternate action is taken.
[src:nltk/stemming] This alternate action may involve several other criteria.
[src:nltk/stemming] The non-existence of an output term may serve to cause the algorithm to try alternate suffix stripping rules.
[src:nltk/stemming] It can be the case that two or more suffix stripping rules apply to the same input term, which creates an ambiguity as to which rule to apply.
[src:nltk/stemming] The algorithm may assign (by human hand or stochastically) a priority to one rule or another.
[src:nltk/stemming] Or the algorithm may reject one rule application because it results in a non-existent term whereas the other overlapping rule does not.
[src:nltk/stemming] For example, given the English term *friendlies*, the algorithm may identify the *ies* suffix and apply the appropriate rule and achieve the result of *friendl*.
[src:nltk/stemming] *Friendl* is likely not found in the lexicon, and therefore the rule is rejected.
[src:nltk/stemming] One improvement upon basic suffix stripping is the use of suffix substitution.
[src:nltk/stemming] Similar to a stripping rule, a substitution rule replaces a suffix with an alternate suffix.
[src:nltk/stemming] For example, there could exist a rule that replaces *ies* with *y*.
[src:nltk/stemming] How this affects the algorithm varies on the algorithm's design.
[src:nltk/stemming] To illustrate, the algorithm may identify that both the *ies* suffix stripping rule as well as the suffix substitution rule apply.
[src:nltk/stemming] Since the stripping rule results in a non-existent term in the lexicon, but the substitution rule does not, the substitution rule is applied instead.
[src:nltk/stemming] In this example, *friendlies* becomes *friendly* instead of *friendl'*.
[src:nltk/stemming] Diving further into the details, a common technique is to apply rules in a cyclical fashion (recursively, as computer scientists would say).
[src:nltk/stemming] After applying the suffix substitution rule in this example scenario, a second pass is made to identify matching rules on the term *friendly*, where the *ly* stripping rule is likely identified and accepted.
[src:nltk/stemming] In summary, *friendlies* becomes (via substitution) *friendly* which becomes (via stripping) *friend*.
[src:nltk/stemming] This example also helps illustrate the difference between a rule-based approach and a brute force approach.
[src:nltk/stemming] In a brute force approach, the algorithm would search for *friendlies* in the set of hundreds of thousands of inflected word forms and ideally find the corresponding root form *friend*.
[src:nltk/stemming] In the rule-based approach, the three rules mentioned above would be applied in succession to converge on the same solution.
[src:nltk/stemming] Chances are that the brute force approach would be slower, as lookup algorithms have a direct access to the solution, while rule-based should try several options, and combinations of them, and then choose which result seems to be the best.
[src:nltk/stemming] A more complex approach to the problem of determining a stem of a word is lemmatisation.
[src:nltk/stemming] This process involves first determining the part of speech of a word, and applying different normalization rules for each part of speech.
[src:nltk/stemming] The part of speech is first detected prior to attempting to find the root since for some languages, the stemming rules change depending on a word's part of speech.
[src:nltk/stemming] This approach is highly conditional upon obtaining the correct lexical category (part of speech).
[src:nltk/stemming] While there is overlap between the normalization rules for certain categories, identifying the wrong category or being unable to produce the right category limits the added benefit of this approach over suffix stripping algorithms.
[src:nltk/stemming] The basic idea is that, if the stemmer is able to grasp more information about the word being stemmed, then it can apply more accurate normalization rules (which unlike suffix stripping rules can also modify the stem).
[src:nltk/stemming] Stochastic algorithms involve using probability to identify the root form of a word.
[src:nltk/stemming] Stochastic algorithms are trained (they "learn") on a table of root form to inflected form relations to develop a probabilistic model.
[src:nltk/stemming] This model is typically expressed in the form of complex linguistic rules, similar in nature to those in suffix stripping or lemmatisation.
[src:nltk/stemming] Some lemmatisation algorithms are stochastic in that, given a word which may belong to multiple parts of speech, a probability is assigned to each possible part.
[src:nltk/stemming] This may take into account the surrounding words, called the context, or not.
[src:nltk/stemming] Context-free grammars do not take into account any additional information.
[src:nltk/stemming] In either case, after assigning the probabilities to each possible part of speech, the most likely part of speech is chosen, and from there the appropriate normalization rules are applied to the input word to produce the normalized (root) form.
[src:nltk/stemming] Some stemming techniques use the n-gram context of a word to choose the correct stem for a word.
[src:nltk/stemming] Hybrid approaches use two or more of the approaches described above in unison.
[src:nltk/stemming] A simple example is a suffix tree algorithm which first consults a lookup table using brute force.
[src:nltk/stemming] However, instead of trying to store the entire set of relations between words in a given language, the lookup table is kept small and is only used to store a minute amount of "frequent exceptions" like "ran => run".
[src:nltk/stemming] If the word is not in the exception list, apply suffix stripping or lemmatisation and output the result.
[src:nltk/stemming] In linguistics, the term affix refers to either a prefix or a suffix.
[src:nltk/stemming] In addition to dealing with suffixes, several approaches also attempt to remove common prefixes.
[src:nltk/stemming] For example, given the word *indefinitely*, identify that the leading "in" is a prefix that can be removed.
[src:nltk/stemming] Many of the same approaches mentioned earlier apply, but go by the name **affix stripping**.
[src:nltk/stemming] A study of affix stemming for several European languages can be found here.
[src:nltk/stemming] Such algorithms use a stem database (for example a set of documents that contain stem words).
[src:nltk/stemming] These stems, as mentioned above, are not necessarily valid words themselves (but rather common sub-strings, as the "brows" in "browse" and in "browsing").
[src:nltk/stemming] While much of the early academic work in this area was focused on the English language (with significant use of the Porter Stemmer algorithm), many other languages have been investigated.
[src:nltk/stemming] Hebrew and Arabic are still considered difficult research languages for stemming.
[src:nltk/stemming] Multilingual stemming applies morphological rules of two or more languages simultaneously instead of rules for only a single language when interpreting a search query.
[src:nltk/stemming] Commercial systems using multilingual stemming exist.
[src:nltk/stemming] There are two error measurements in stemming algorithms, overstemming and understemming.
[src:nltk/stemming] Overstemming is an error where two separate inflected words are stemmed to the same root, but should not have been—a false positive.
[src:nltk/stemming] Understemming is an error where two separate inflected words should be stemmed to the same root, but are not—a false negative.
[src:nltk/stemming] Stemming algorithms attempt to minimize each type of error, although reducing one type can lead to increasing the other.
[src:nltk/stemming] For example, the widely used Porter stemmer stems "universal", "university", and "universe" to "univers".
[src:nltk/stemming] This is a case of overstemming: though these three words are etymologically related, their modern meanings are in widely different domains, so treating them as synonyms in a search engine will likely reduce the relevance of the search results.
[src:nltk/stemming] An example of understemming in the Porter stemmer is "alumnus" → "alumnu", "alumni" → "alumni", "alumna"/"alumnae" → "alumna".
[src:nltk/stemming] This English word keeps Latin morphology, and so these near-synonyms are not conflated.
[src:nltk/stemming] Stemming is used as an approximate method for grouping words with a similar basic meaning together.
[src:nltk/stemming] For example, a text mentioning "daffodils" is probably closely related to a text mentioning "daffodil" (without the s).
[src:nltk/stemming] But in some cases, words with the same morphological stem have idiomatic meanings which are not closely related: a user searching for "marketing" will not be satisfied by most documents mentioning "markets" but not "marketing".
[src:nltk/stemming] Stemmers can be used as elements in query systems such as Web search engines.
[src:nltk/stemming] The effectiveness of stemming for English query systems were soon found to be rather limited, however, and this has led early information retrieval researchers to deem stemming irrelevant in general.
[src:nltk/stemming] An alternative approach, based on searching for n-grams rather than stems, may be used instead.
[src:nltk/stemming] Also, stemmers may provide greater benefits in other languages than English.
[src:nltk/stemming] Stemming is used to determine domain vocabularies in domain analysis.
[src:nltk/stemming] Many commercial companies have been using stemming since at least the 1980s and have produced algorithmic and lexical stemmers in many languages.
[src:nltk/stemming] The Snowball stemmers have been compared with commercial lexical stemmers with varying results.
[src:nltk/stemming] Google Search adopted word stemming in 2003.
[src:nltk/stemming] Previously a search for "fish" would not have returned "fishing".
[src:nltk/stemming] Other software search algorithms vary in their use of word stemming.
[src:nltk/stemming] Programs that simply search for substrings will obviously find "fish" in "fishing" but when searching for "fishes" will not find occurrences of the word "fish".
[src:nltk/stemming] Stemming is used as a task in pre-processing texts before performing text mining analyses on it.
[src:nltk/text-corpus] In linguistics and natural language processing, a **corpus** (pl.: **corpora**) or **text corpus** is a dataset, consisting of natively digital and older, digitalized, language resources, either annotated or unannotated.
[src:nltk/text-corpus] Annotated, they have been used in corpus linguistics for statistical hypothesis testing, checking occurrences or validating linguistic rules within a specific language territory.
[src:nltk/text-corpus] A corpus may contain texts in a single language (*monolingual corpus*) or text data in multiple languages (*multilingual corpus*).
[src:nltk/text-corpus] In order to make the corpora more useful for doing linguistic research, they are often subjected to a process known as annotation.
[src:nltk/text-corpus] An example of annotating a corpus is part-of-speech tagging, or *POS-tagging*, in which information about each word's part of speech (verb, noun, adjective, etc.) is added to the corpus in the form of *tags*.
[src:nltk/text-corpus] Another example is indicating the lemma (base) form of each word.
[src:nltk/text-corpus] When the language of the corpus is not a working language of the researchers who use it, interlinear glossing is used to make the annotation bilingual.
[src:nltk/text-corpus] Some corpora have further *structured* levels of analysis applied.
[src:nltk/text-corpus] In particular, smaller corpora may be fully parsed.
[src:nltk/text-corpus] Such corpora are usually called Treebanks or Parsed Corpora.
[src:nltk/text-corpus] The difficulty of ensuring that the entire corpus is completely and consistently annotated means that these corpora are usually smaller, containing around one to three million words.
[src:nltk/text-corpus] Other levels of linguistic structured analysis are possible, including annotations for morphology, semantics and pragmatics.
[src:nltk/text-corpus] Corpora are the main knowledge base in corpus linguistics.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A rule-based program, performing lexical tokenization, is called *tokenizer*, or *scanner*, although *scanner* is also a term for the first stage of a lexer.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A lexer forms the first phase of a compiler frontend in processing.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Lexers and parsers are most often used for compilers, but can be used for other computer language tools, such as prettyprinters or linters.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Lexing can be divided into two stages: the *scanning*, which segments the input string into syntactic units called *lexemes* and categorizes these into token classes, and the *evaluating*, which converts lexemes into processed values.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Lexers are generally quite simple, with most of the complexity deferred to the syntactic analysis or semantic analysis phases, and can often be generated by a lexer generator, notably lex or derivatives.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] However, lexers can sometimes include some complexity, such as phrase structure processing to make input easier and simplify the parser, and may be written partly or fully by hand, either to support more features or for performance.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing is not equal to what is called lexeme in linguistics.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing can be equal to the linguistic equivalent only in analytic languages, such as English, but not in highly synthetic languages, such as fusional languages.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] What is called a lexeme in rule-based natural language processing is more similar to what is called a word in linguistics (not to be confused with a word in computer architecture), although in some cases it may be more similar to a morpheme.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A *lexical token* is a string with an assigned and thus identified meaning, in contrast to the probabilistic token used in large language models.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A lexical token consists of a *token name* and an optional *token value*.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The token name is a category of a rule-based lexical unit.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A token name is what might be termed a part of speech in linguistics.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] the string is not implicitly segmented on spaces, as a natural language speaker would do.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The raw input, the 43 characters, must be explicitly split into the 9 tokens with a given space delimiter (i.e., matching the string `" "` or regular expression `/\s{1}/`).
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] When a token class represents more than one possible lexeme, the lexer often saves enough information to reproduce the original lexeme, so that it can be used in semantic analysis.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The parser typically retrieves this information from the lexer and stores it in the abstract syntax tree.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This is necessary in order to avoid information loss in the case where numbers may also be valid identifiers.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Tokens are identified based on the specific rules of the lexer.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Some methods used to identify tokens include regular expressions, specific sequences of characters termed a flag, specific separating characters called delimiters, and explicit definition by a dictionary.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Special characters, including punctuation characters, are commonly used by lexers to identify tokens because of their natural use in written and programming languages.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A lexical analyzer generally does nothing with combinations of tokens, a task left for a parser.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] For example, a typical lexical analyzer recognizes parentheses as tokens but does nothing to ensure that each "(" is matched with a ")".
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] When a lexer feeds tokens to the parser, the representation used is typically an enumerated type, which is a list of number representations.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] For example, "Identifier" can be represented with 0, "Assignment operator" with 1, "Addition operator" with 2, etc.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Tokens are often defined by regular expressions, which are understood by a lexical analyzer generator such as lex, or handcoded equivalent finite-state automata.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The lexical analyzer (generated automatically by a tool like lex or hand-crafted) reads in a stream of characters, identifies the lexemes in the stream, and categorizes them into tokens.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] If the lexer finds an invalid token, it will report an error.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] From there, the interpreted data may be loaded into data structures for general use, interpretation, or compiling.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The specification of a programming language often includes a set of rules, the lexical grammar, which defines the lexical syntax.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The lexical syntax is usually a regular language, with the grammar rules consisting of regular expressions; they define the set of possible character sequences (lexemes) of a token.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A lexer recognizes strings, and for each kind of string found, the lexical program takes an action, most simply producing a token.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Two important common lexical categories are white space and comments.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] These are also defined in the grammar and processed by the lexer but may be discarded (not producing any tokens) and considered *non-significant*, at most separating two tokens (as in `if x` instead of `ifx`).
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] There are two important exceptions to this.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] First, in off-side rule languages that delimit blocks with indenting, initial whitespace is significant, as it determines block structure, and is generally handled at the lexer level; see phrase structure, below.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Secondly, in some uses of lexers, comments and whitespace must be preserved – for examples, a prettyprinter also needs to output the comments and some debugging tools may provide messages to the programmer showing the original source code.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] In the 1960s, notably for ALGOL, whitespace and comments were eliminated as part of the line reconstruction phase (the initial phase of the compiler frontend), but this separate phase has been eliminated and these are now handled by the lexer.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The first stage, the *scanner*, is usually based on a finite-state machine (FSM).
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] It has encoded within it information on the possible sequences of characters that can be contained within any of the tokens it handles (individual instances of these character sequences are termed lexemes).
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] For example, an *integer* lexeme may contain any sequence of numerical digit characters.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] In some languages, the lexeme creation rules are more complex and may involve backtracking over previously read characters.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] For example, in C, one 'L' character is not enough to distinguish between an identifier that begins with 'L' and a wide-character string literal.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A lexeme, however, is only a string of characters known to be of a certain kind (e.g., a string literal, a sequence of letters).
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The second stage of a lexical analyzer, the *evaluator*, goes over the characters of the lexeme to produce a *value* containing relevant information for the parser.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The lexeme's type combined with its value is what properly constitutes a *token*.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The value in the token can be whatever is deemed necessary for the parser to interpret a token of that type.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The evaluator may also suppress a lexeme entirely, concealing it from the parser, which is useful for whitespace and comments.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This is practical if the list of tokens is small, but lexers generated by automated tooling as part of a compiler-compiler toolchain are more practical for a larger number of potential tokens.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] These tools generally accept regular expressions that describe the tokens allowed in the input stream.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Each regular expression is associated with a production rule in the lexical grammar of the programming language that evaluates the lexemes matching the regular expression.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] These tools may generate source code that can be compiled and executed or construct a state transition table for a finite-state machine (which is plugged into template code for compiling and executing).
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Regular expressions compactly represent patterns that the characters in lexemes might follow.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] For example, for an English-based language, an IDENTIFIER token might be any English alphabetic character or an underscore, followed by any number of instances of ASCII alphanumeric characters and/or underscores.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This could be represented compactly by the string `[a-zA-Z_][a-zA-Z_0-9]*`.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This means "any character a-z, A-Z or _, followed by 0 or more of a-z, A-Z, _ or 0-9".
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] It takes a full parser to recognize such patterns in their full generality.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A parser can push parentheses on a stack and then try to pop them off and see if the stack is empty at the end (see example in the *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs* book).
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Typically, lexical tokenization occurs at the word level.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] However, it is sometimes difficult to define what is meant by a "word".
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] In languages that use inter-word spaces (such as most that use the Latin alphabet, and most programming languages), this approach is fairly straightforward.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] However, even here there are many edge cases such as contractions, hyphenated words, emoticons, and larger constructs such as URIs (which for some purposes may count as single tokens).
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A classic example is "New York-based", which a naive tokenizer may break at the space even though the better break is (arguably) at the hyphen.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Tokenization is particularly difficult for languages written in scriptio continua, which exhibit no word boundaries, such as Ancient Greek, Chinese, or Thai.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Agglutinative languages, such as Korean, also make tokenization tasks complicated.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Some ways to address the more difficult problems include developing more complex heuristics, querying a table of common special cases, or fitting the tokens to a language model that identifies collocations in a later processing step.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Lexers are often generated by a *lexer generator*, analogous to parser generators, and such tools often come together.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The most established is lex, paired with the yacc parser generator, or rather some of their many reimplementations, like flex (often paired with GNU Bison).
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] These generators are a form of domain-specific language, taking in a lexical specification – generally regular expressions with some markup – and emitting a lexer.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] These tools yield very fast development, which is very important in early development, both to get a working lexer and because a language specification may change often.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Further, they often provide advanced features, such as pre- and post-conditions which are hard to program by hand.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] However, an automatically generated lexer may lack flexibility, and thus may require some manual modification, or an all-manually written lexer.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Lexer performance is a concern, and optimizing is worthwhile, more so in stable languages where the lexer runs very often (such as C or HTML). lex/flex-generated lexers are reasonably fast, but improvements of two to three times are possible using more tuned generators.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Hand-written lexers are sometimes used, but modern lexer generators produce faster lexers than most hand-coded ones.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The lex/flex family of generators uses a table-driven approach which is much less efficient than the directly coded approach.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] With the latter approach the generator produces an engine that directly jumps to follow-up states via goto statements.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Tools like re2c have proven to produce engines that are between two and three times faster than flex produced engines.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] It is in general difficult to hand-write analyzers that perform better than engines generated by these latter tools.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Lexical analysis mainly segments the input stream of characters into tokens, simply grouping the characters into pieces and categorizing them.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] However, the lexing may be significantly more complex; most simply, lexers may omit tokens or insert added tokens.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Omitting tokens, notably whitespace and comments, is very common when these are not needed by the compiler.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Less commonly, added tokens may be inserted.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This is done mainly to group tokens into statements, or statements into blocks, to simplify the parser.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Line continuation is a feature of some languages where a newline is normally a statement terminator.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Most often, ending a line with a backslash (immediately followed by a newline) results in the line being *continued* – the following line is *joined* to the prior line.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This is generally done in the lexer: The backslash and newline are discarded, rather than the newline being tokenized.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Examples include bash, other shell scripts and Python.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Many languages use the semicolon as a statement terminator.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Most often this is mandatory, but in some languages the semicolon is optional in many contexts.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This is mainly done at the lexer level, where the lexer outputs a semicolon into the token stream, despite one not being present in the input character stream, and is termed *semicolon insertion* or *automatic semicolon insertion*.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] In these cases, semicolons are part of the formal phrase grammar of the language, but may not be found in input text, as they can be inserted by the lexer.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Optional semicolons or other terminators or separators are also sometimes handled at the parser level, notably in the case of trailing commas or semicolons.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is a feature of BCPL and its distant descendant Go, though it is absent in B or C.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is present in JavaScript, though the rules are somewhat complex and much-criticized; to avoid bugs, some recommend always using semicolons, while others use initial semicolons, termed defensive semicolons, at the start of potentially ambiguous statements.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] The off-side rule (blocks determined by indenting) can be implemented in the lexer, as in Python, where increasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting an INDENT token and decreasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting one or more DEDENT tokens.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] These tokens correspond to the opening brace `{` and closing brace `}` in languages that use braces for blocks and means that the phrase grammar does not depend on whether braces or indenting are used.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This requires that the lexer hold state, namely a stack of indent levels, and thus can detect changes in indenting when this changes, and thus the lexical grammar is not context-free: INDENT–DEDENT depend on the contextual information of prior indent levels.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Generally lexical grammars are context-free, or almost so, and thus require no looking back or ahead, or backtracking, which allows a simple, clean, and efficient implementation.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] This also allows simple one-way communication from lexer to parser, without needing any information flowing back to the lexer.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] These examples all only require lexical context, and while they complicate a lexer somewhat, they are invisible to the parser and later phases.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] A more complex example is the lexer hack in C, where the token class of a sequence of characters cannot be determined until the semantic analysis phase since typedef names and variable names are lexically identical but constitute different token classes.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] Thus in the hack, the lexer calls the semantic analyzer (say, symbol table) and checks if the sequence requires a typedef name.
[src:nltk/tokenization-lexical-analysis] In this case, information must flow back not from the parser only, but from the semantic analyzer back to the lexer, which complicates design.
[src:nltk/wordnet] WordNet was first created in 1985, in English only, in the Cognitive Science Laboratory of Princeton University under the direction of psychology professor George Armitage Miller.
[src:nltk/wordnet] It was later directed by Christiane Fellbaum.
[src:nltk/wordnet] The project was initially funded by the U.S.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Office of Naval Research, and later also by other U.S. government agencies including the DARPA, the National Science Foundation, the Disruptive Technology Office (formerly the Advanced Research and Development Activity) and REFLEX.
[src:nltk/wordnet] George Miller and Christiane Fellbaum received the 2006 Antonio Zampolli Prize for their work with WordNet.
[src:nltk/wordnet] The Global WordNet Association is a non-commercial organization that provides a platform for discussing, sharing and connecting WordNets for all languages in the world.
[src:nltk/wordnet] The database contains 155,327 words organized in 175,979 synsets for a total of 207,016 word-sense pairs; in compressed form, it is about 12 megabytes in size.
[src:nltk/wordnet] It includes the lexical categories nouns, verbs, adjectives and adverbs but ignores prepositions, determiners and other function words.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Words from the same lexical category that are roughly synonymous are grouped into synsets, which include simplex words as well as collocations like "eat out" and "car pool." The different senses of a polysemous word form are assigned to different synsets.
[src:nltk/wordnet] A synset's meaning is further clarified with a short defining *gloss* and one or more usage examples.
[src:nltk/wordnet] All synsets are connected by means of semantic relations.
[src:nltk/wordnet] These semantic relations hold among all members of the linked synsets.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Individual synset members (words) can also be connected with lexical relations.
[src:nltk/wordnet] For example, (one sense of) the noun "director" is linked to (one sense of) the verb "direct" from which it is derived via a "morphosemantic" link.
[src:nltk/wordnet] The morphology functions of the software distributed with the database try to deduce the lemma or stem form of a word from the user's input.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Irregular forms are stored in a list, and looking up "ate" will return "eat," for example.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Both nouns and verbs are organized into hierarchies, defined by hypernym or *IS A* relationships.
[src:nltk/wordnet] For instance, one sense of the word *dog* is found following hypernym hierarchy; the words at the same level represent synset members.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Each set of synonyms has a unique index.
[src:nltk/wordnet] At the top level, these hierarchies are organized into 25 beginner "trees" for nouns and 15 for verbs (called *lexicographic files* at a maintenance level).
[src:nltk/wordnet] All are linked to a unique beginner synset, "entity".
[src:nltk/wordnet] Noun hierarchies are far deeper than verb hierarchies.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Adjectives are not organized into hierarchical trees.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Instead, two "central" antonyms such as "hot" and "cold" form binary poles, while 'satellite' synonyms such as "steaming" and "chilly" connect to their respective poles via a "similarity" relations.
[src:nltk/wordnet] The adjectives can be visualized in this way as "dumbbells" rather than as "trees".
[src:nltk/wordnet] The initial goal of the WordNet project was to build a lexical database that would be consistent with theories of human semantic memory developed in the late 1960s.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Psychological experiments indicated that speakers organized their knowledge of concepts in an economic, hierarchical fashion.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Retrieval time required to access conceptual knowledge seemed to be directly related to the number of hierarchies the speaker needed to "traverse" to access the knowledge.
[src:nltk/wordnet] While such psycholinguistic experiments and the underlying theories have been subject to criticism, some of WordNet's organization is consistent with experimental evidence.
[src:nltk/wordnet] For example, anomic aphasia selectively affects speakers' ability to produce words from a specific semantic category, a WordNet hierarchy.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Antonymous adjectives (WordNet's central adjectives in the dumbbell structure) are found to co-occur far more frequently than chance, a fact that has been found to hold for many languages.
[src:nltk/wordnet] WordNet is sometimes called an ontology, a persistent claim that its creators do not make.
[src:nltk/wordnet] The hypernym/hyponym relationships among the noun synsets can be interpreted as specialization relations among conceptual categories.
[src:nltk/wordnet] In other words, WordNet can be interpreted and used as a lexical ontology in the computer science sense.
[src:nltk/wordnet] However, such an ontology should be corrected before being used, because it contains hundreds of basic semantic inconsistencies; for example there are, (i) common specializations for exclusive categories and (ii) redundancies in the specialization hierarchy.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Furthermore, transforming WordNet into a lexical ontology usable for knowledge representation should normally also involve (i) distinguishing the specialization relations into *subtypeOf* and *instanceOf* relations, and (ii) associating intuitive unique identifiers to each category.
[src:nltk/wordnet] WordNet has also been converted to a formal specification, by means of a hybrid bottom-up top-down methodology to automatically extract association relations from it and interpret these associations in terms of a set of conceptual relations, formally defined in the DOLCE foundational ontology.
[src:nltk/wordnet] In most works that claim to have integrated WordNet into ontologies, the content of WordNet has not simply been corrected when it seemed necessary; instead, it has been heavily reinterpreted and updated whenever suitable.
[src:nltk/wordnet] This was the case when, for example, the top-level ontology of WordNet was restructured according to the OntoClean-based approach, or when it was used as a primary source for constructing the lower classes of the SENSUS ontology.
[src:nltk/wordnet] The most widely discussed limitation of WordNet (and related resources like ImageNet) is that some of the semantic relations are more suited to concrete concepts than to abstract concepts.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Many of the concepts in WordNet are specific to certain languages and the most accurate reported mapping between languages is 94%.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Synonyms, hyponyms, meronyms, and antonyms occur in all languages with a WordNet so far, but other semantic relationships are language-specific.
[src:nltk/wordnet] This limits the interoperability across languages.
[src:nltk/wordnet] However, it also makes WordNet a resource for highlighting and studying the differences between languages, so it is not necessarily a limitation for all use cases.
[src:nltk/wordnet] WordNet does not include information about the etymology or the pronunciation of words and it contains only limited information about usage.
[src:nltk/wordnet] WordNet aims to cover most everyday words and does not include much domain-specific terminology.
[src:nltk/wordnet] WordNet is the most commonly used computational lexicon of English for word-sense disambiguation (WSD), a task aimed at assigning the context-appropriate meanings (i.e. synset members) to words in a text.
[src:nltk/wordnet] However, it has been argued that WordNet encodes sense distinctions that are too fine-grained.
[src:nltk/wordnet] This issue prevents WSD systems from achieving a level of performance comparable to that of humans, who do not always agree when confronted with the task of selecting a sense from a dictionary that matches a word in a context.
[src:nltk/wordnet] The granularity issue has been tackled by proposing clustering methods that automatically group together similar senses of the same word.
[src:nltk/wordnet] WordNet includes words that can be perceived as pejorative or offensive.
[src:nltk/wordnet] The interpretation of a word can change over time and between social groups, so it is not always possible for WordNet to define a word as "pejorative" or "offensive" in isolation.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Therefore, people using WordNet must apply their own methods to identify offensive or pejorative words.
[src:nltk/wordnet] However, this limitation is true of other lexical resources like dictionaries and thesauruses, which also contain pejorative and offensive words.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Some dictionaries indicate words that are pejoratives, but do not include all the contexts in which words might be acceptable or offensive to different social groups.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Therefore, people using dictionaries must apply their own methods to identify all offensive words.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Some wordnets were subsequently created for other languages.
[src:nltk/wordnet] A 2012 survey lists the wordnets and their availability.
[src:nltk/wordnet] The Open Multilingual Wordnet provides access to open licensed wordnets in a variety of languages.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Version 1 is linked to the Princeton Wordnet of English, while version 2 uses an independent index (the Collaborative Interlingual Index).
[src:nltk/wordnet] The goal is to make it easy to use wordnets in multiple languages.
[src:nltk/wordnet] WordNet has been used for a number of purposes in information systems, including word-sense disambiguation, information retrieval, automatic text classification, automatic text summarization, machine translation and even automatic crossword puzzle generation.
[src:nltk/wordnet] A common use of WordNet is to determine the similarity between words.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Various algorithms have been proposed, including measuring the distance among words and synsets in WordNet's graph structure, such as by counting the number of edges among synsets.
[src:nltk/wordnet] The intuition is that the closer two words or synsets are, the closer their meaning.
[src:nltk/wordnet] A number of WordNet-based word similarity algorithms are implemented in a Perl package called WordNet::Similarity, and in a Python package called NLTK.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Other more sophisticated WordNet-based similarity techniques include ADW, whose implementation is available in Java.
[src:nltk/wordnet] WordNet can also be used to inter-link other vocabularies.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Princeton maintains a list of related projects that includes links to some of the widely used application programming interfaces available for accessing WordNet using various programming languages and environments.
[src:nltk/wordnet] WordNet is connected to several databases of the Semantic Web.
[src:nltk/wordnet] WordNet is also commonly reused via mappings between the WordNet synsets and the categories from ontologies.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Most often, only the top-level categories of WordNet are mapped.
[src:nltk/wordnet] The Global WordNet Association (GWA) is a public and non-commercial organization that provides a platform for discussing, sharing and connecting wordnets for all languages in the world.
[src:nltk/wordnet] The GWA also promotes the standardization of wordnets across languages, to ensure its uniformity in enumerating the synsets in human languages.
[src:nltk/wordnet] The GWA keeps a list of wordnets developed around the world.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Projects such as BalkaNet and EuroWordNet made it feasible to create standalone wordnets linked to the original one.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Two such projects were the Russian WordNet, patronized by Petersburg State University of Means of Communication and led by S.A.
[src:nltk/wordnet] Yablonsky, and Russnet, by Saint Petersburg State University.
